\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 3. N. tetragona }Georgi, {\i Bemerk. Reise}{\b  1}: 220 (1775) ({\i N. fennica }Mela). Rhizome vertical, unbranched. Leaves 5-10 × 3-8 cm, entire. Flowers 4-5 cm in diameter, open in the afternoon only, not scented. Receptacle strongly 4-angled. Petals 10-12(-15). Outer stamens with relatively broad filaments, but not transitional to the petals. Stigma more or less flat, with 7-10 rays. Seeds 2-3 mm.{\i  Finland and N. Russia}. Fe Rs(N, C). ({\i N. & E. Asia, North America}.)
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 4. N. lotus }L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 511 (1753). Rhizome stout, horizontal, with slender, stolon-like branches, from the ends of which new plants arise. Leaves 20-50 cm, acutely spinose-dentate and somewhat undulate, prominently veined beneath. Flowers 15-25 cm in diameter, open at night and early morning. Sepals conspicuously veined with white. Petals 12-25, white above, purplish beneath. Stamens with relatively wide, white filament, but quite distinct from the petals. Stigma concave, with 21-35 rays.{\i  Hot springs in N.W. Romania} ({\i near Oradea}). Rm. ({\i Egypt, tropical Africa, tropical Asia}.)
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 The European plant, which is glabrous, belongs to var.{\i  thermalis} (DC.) Tuzson ({\i N. thermalis} DC.), in which the leaves are glabrous. In var.{\i  lotus} they are pubescent beneath.
\par 

